# ShipWeekly.dev — Cursor Rules

## Who You Are
You are a senior full stack developer building ShipWeekly.dev — a weekly product launch platform for indie hackers, SaaS founders, and open source makers. You write clean, production-ready TypeScript. You never take shortcuts that will cause problems later.

## Tech Stack — Exact Versions
- Framework: Next.js 15 with App Router and TypeScript
- Styling: Tailwind CSS + shadcn/ui (New York style, zinc base)
- Auth: Clerk (@clerk/nextjs)
- Database: Neon Postgres via @neondatabase/serverless
- ORM: Drizzle ORM with drizzle-kit
- Validation: Zod
- Storage: Cloudinary
- Email: Resend
- IDs: nanoid
- Utils: clsx + tailwind-merge

## Folder Structure Rules
- All source code lives in /app, /components, /lib
- API routes live in app/api/
- Server actions live in lib/actions/
- Database queries live in lib/db/queries.ts
- Database schema lives in lib/db/schema.ts
- Database client lives in lib/db/index.ts
- Auth config lives in lib/auth.ts
- Reusable components live in /components
- shadcn primitives live in components/ui/
- Discussion/forum logic lives in lib/actions/ and lib/db/queries.ts
- Newsletter logic lives in lib/actions/ and api/newsletter/
- Collection logic lives in lib/actions/ and api/collections/
- Never create folders outside this structure without asking

## TypeScript Rules
- Never use `any` type. Ever.
- Always define explicit return types on functions
- Always define prop types as interfaces above the component
- Use type for unions, interface for object shapes
- Always handle null and undefined explicitly

## Next.js Rules
- Default to server components. Only use client components when you need useState, useEffect, event handlers, or browser APIs
- Mark client components with "use client" at the top
- Use server actions for form submissions — never API routes for forms
- Use API routes only for external webhooks and third party callbacks
- Use generateMetadata for SEO on every public page
- Use Next.js Image component for all images. Never use raw img tags
- Use Next.js Link component for all internal navigation. Never use raw a tags for internal links

## Drizzle ORM Rules
- Always import tables and relations from lib/db/schema.ts
- Always use the db client from lib/db/index.ts
- Never write raw SQL unless Drizzle cannot express the query
- Always handle database errors with try catch
- Always run writes (insert, update, delete) through transactions when multiple tables are affected
- Never expose database errors directly to the client

## API Route Rules
- Always validate request body with Zod before touching the database
- Always check authentication before any protected operation
- Return consistent response shapes — always { success: true, data: ... } or { success: false, error: "..." }
- Use proper HTTP status codes — 200, 201, 400, 401, 403, 404, 429, 500
- Never return stack traces or internal error messages to the client

## Auth Rules
- Get user ID using auth() from @clerk/nextjs/server in server components and API routes
- Get full user using currentUser() from @clerk/nextjs/server
- Never trust client-sent user IDs. Always get user ID from auth()
- Check auth() exists before any protected database operation
- Map Clerk userId to your users table via clerk_user_id column

## Component Rules
- One component per file
- File name matches component name in kebab-case
- Always use shadcn components before building custom ones
- Use cn() utility from lib/utils.ts for conditional classNames
- Never use inline styles
- All components must be responsive — mobile first
- Screenshot galleries use the screenshot-gallery.tsx component
- Collection cards use the collection-card.tsx component
- Discussion cards use the discussion-card.tsx component
- Newsletter forms use the newsletter-form.tsx component
- Product badges use the badge-display.tsx component

## Validation Rules
- Every form input is validated with Zod on the server
- Define Zod schemas in the same file as the server action that uses them
- Return field-level errors back to the form, not just generic messages

## Error Handling Rules
- Every async function has try catch
- Log errors with console.error on the server
- Show user-friendly error messages on the client — never raw error messages
- Use loading states on all async UI interactions

## What To Never Do
- Never install a new package without asking first
- Never use `--force` or `--legacy-peer-deps` when installing packages (resolve version conflicts properly)
- Never modify lib/db/schema.ts without being explicitly asked
- Never run database migrations automatically
- Never commit .env.local or any secrets
- Never use localStorage — use server sessions via Clerk
- Never skip Zod validation
- Never use alert() or confirm() — use shadcn Dialog or Toast
- Never write CSS outside of Tailwind classes
- Never create a new file structure that doesn't match the folder rules above
- Never modify discussion/collection/newsletter tables without migration planning
- Never handle OAuth flows manually — Clerk manages this entirely
- Never process payments without verifying Dodo webhook signatures

## Security & Dependency Rules
- Package Installs: Always check package weekly downloads and last publish date before installing. Avoid abandoned packages.
- Peer Dependencies: If a peer dependency conflict occurs, DO NOT force install. Find compatible versions of the libraries. Force installing breaks production builds.
- XSS Prevention: Never use `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` unless explicitly processing sanitized markdown from a trusted library.
- SQL Injection: Never use raw SQL template literals without Drizzle's `sql` helper. Always rely on Drizzle's parameterized queries.
- CSRF Protection: Next.js Server Actions automatically protect against CSRF, so always use them for mutations instead of API routes.
